# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bioconversion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion-of-glycerol-to-1-3-propanediol] It is mainly used as a building block in the production of polymers such as polytrimethylene terephthalate.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion-of-glycerol-to-1-3-propanediol] 1,3-Propanediol can be formulated into a variety of industrial products including composites, adhesives, laminates, coatings, moldings, aliphatic polyesters, and copolyesters.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion-of-glycerol-to-1-3-propanediol] It is used as an antifreeze and as a component in wood paint.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion-of-glycerol-to-1-3-propanediol] 1,3-Propanediol is mainly produced by the hydration of acrolein.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion-of-glycerol-to-1-3-propanediol] An alternative route involves the hydroformylation of ethylene oxide to form 3-hydroxypropionaldehyde.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion-of-glycerol-to-1-3-propanediol] The aldehyde is subsequently hydrogenated to give 1,3-propanediol.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion-of-glycerol-to-1-3-propanediol] 1,3-Propanediol does not appear to pose a significant hazard via inhalation of either the vapor or a vapor/aerosol mixture.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] Another example of bioconversion is the conversion of organic materials, such as plant or animal waste, into usable products or energy sources by biological processes or agents, such as certain microorganisms, some detritivores or enzymes.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] In the US, the Bioconversion Science and Technology group performs multidisciplinary R&D for the Department of Energy's (DOE) relevant applications of bioprocessing, especially with biomass.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] Bioprocessing combines the disciplines of chemical engineering, microbiology and biochemistry.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] The Group 's primary role is investigation of the use of microorganism, microbial consortia and microbial enzymes in bioenergy research.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] New cellulosic ethanol conversion processes have enabled the variety and volume of feedstock that can be bioconverted to expand rapidly.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] Feedstock now includes materials derived from plant or animal waste such as paper, auto-fluff, tires, fabric, construction materials, municipal solid waste (MSW), sludge, sewage, etc.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] 1 -**Enzymatic hydrolysis** - a single source of feedstock, switchgrass for example, is mixed with strong enzymes which convert a portion of cellulosic material into sugars which can then be fermented into ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] Genencor and Novozymes are two companies that have received United States government Department of Energy funding for research into reducing the cost of cellulase, a key enzyme in the production cellulosic ethanol by this process.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] 2 - **Synthesis gas fermentation** - a blend of feedstock, not exceeding 30% water, is gasified in a closed environment into a syngas containing mostly carbon monoxide and hydrogen.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] The cooled syngas is then converted into usable products through exposure to bacteria or other catalysts.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] BRI Energy, LLC is a company whose pilot plant in Fayetteville, Arkansas is currently using synthesis gas fermentation to convert a variety of waste into ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] After gasification, anaerobic bacteria (*Clostridium ljungdahlii*) are used to convert the syngas (CO, CO2, and H2) into ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] The heat generated by gasification is also used to co-generate excess electricity.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] 3 - **C.O.R.S. and Grub Composting** are sustainable technologies that employ organisms that feed on organic matter to reduce and convert organic waste in to high quality feedstuff and oil rich material for the biodiesel industry.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] Organizations pioneering this approach to waste management are EAWAG, ESR International, Prota Culture and BIOCONVERSION that created the *e*-CORS® system to meet large scale organic waste management needs and environmental sustainability in both urban and livestock farming reality.
[src:bioconversion/bioconversion] This type of engineered system introduces a substantial innovation represented by the automatic modulation of the treatment, able to adapt conditions of the system to the biology of the scavenger used, improving their performances and the power of this technology.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] It is a trace gas in Earth's atmosphere at 428 parts per million (ppm), or about 0.043% (as of July 2025) having risen from pre-industrial levels of 280 ppm or about 0.028%.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Burning fossil fuels is the main cause of these increased CO2 concentrations, which are the primary cause of climate change.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Its concentration in Earth's pre-industrial atmosphere since late in the Precambrian was regulated by organisms and geological features.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Plants, algae and cyanobacteria use energy from sunlight to synthesize carbohydrates from carbon dioxide and water in a process called photosynthesis, which produces oxygen as a waste product.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In turn, oxygen is consumed and CO2 is released as waste by all aerobic organisms when they metabolize organic compounds to produce energy by respiration.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is released from organic materials when they decay or combust, such as in forest fires.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in water, it forms carbonate and mainly bicarbonate (HCO3–), which causes ocean acidification as atmospheric CO2 levels increase.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is 53% denser than dry air, but is long-lived and thoroughly mixes in the atmosphere.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] About half of excess CO2 emissions to the atmosphere are absorbed by land and ocean carbon sinks.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] These sinks can become saturated and are volatile, as decay and wildfires result in the CO2 being released back into the atmosphere.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] CO2, or the carbon it holds, is eventually sequestered (stored for the long term) in rocks and organic deposits like coal, petroleum and natural gas.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Nearly all CO2 produced by humans goes into the atmosphere.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Less than 1% of CO2 produced annually is put to commercial use, mostly in the fertilizer industry and in the oil and gas industry for enhanced oil recovery.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Other commercial applications include food and beverage production, metal fabrication, cooling, fire suppression and stimulating plant growth in greenhouses.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The symmetry of a carbon dioxide molecule is linear and centrosymmetric at its equilibrium geometry.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The length of the carbon–oxygen bond in carbon dioxide is 116.3 pm, noticeably shorter than the roughly 140 pm length of a typical single C–O bond, and shorter than most other C–O multiply bonded functional groups such as carbonyls.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Since it is centrosymmetric, the molecule has no electric dipole moment.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] As a linear triatomic molecule, CO2 has four vibrational modes as shown in the diagram.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In the symmetric and the antisymmetric stretching modes, the atoms move along the axis of the molecule.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] There are two bending modes, which are degenerate, meaning that they have the same frequency and same energy, because of the symmetry of the molecule.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] When a molecule touches a surface or touches another molecule, the two bending modes can differ in frequency because the interaction is different for the two modes.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Some of the vibrational modes are observed in the infrared (IR) spectrum: the antisymmetric stretching mode at wavenumber 2349 cm−1 (wavelength 4.25 μm) and the degenerate pair of bending modes at 667 cm−1 (wavelength 15.0 μm).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The symmetric stretching mode does not create an electric dipole so is not observed in IR spectroscopy, but it is detected in Raman spectroscopy at 1388 cm−1 (wavelength 7.20 μm), with a Fermi resonance doublet at 1285 cm−1.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In the gas phase, carbon dioxide molecules undergo significant vibrational motions and do not keep a fixed structure.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] However, in a Coulomb explosion imaging experiment, an instantaneous image of the molecular structure can be deduced.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Such an experiment has been performed for carbon dioxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The result of this experiment, and the conclusion of theoretical calculations based on an ab initio potential energy surface of the molecule, is that none of the molecules in the gas phase are ever exactly linear.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This counter-intuitive result is trivially due to the fact that the nuclear motion volume element vanishes for linear geometries.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This is so for all molecules except diatomic molecules.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is soluble in water, in which it reversibly forms H2CO3 (carbonic acid), which is a weak acid, because its ionization in water is incomplete.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Hence, the majority of the carbon dioxide is not converted into carbonic acid, but remains as CO2 molecules, not affecting the pH.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The relative concentrations of CO2, H2CO3, and the deprotonated forms HCO3– (bicarbonate) and CO32– (carbonate) depend on the pH.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] As shown in a Bjerrum plot, in neutral or slightly alkaline water (pH > 6.5), the bicarbonate form predominates (>50%) becoming the most prevalent (>95%) at the pH of seawater.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In very alkaline water (pH > 10.4), the predominant (>50%) form is carbonate.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The oceans, being mildly alkaline with typical pH = 8.2–8.5, contain about 120 mg of bicarbonate per liter.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] where the denominator includes only covalently bound H2CO3 and does not include hydrated CO2(aq).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Since most of the dissolved CO2 remains as CO2 molecules, *K*a1(apparent) has a much larger denominator and a much smaller value than the true *K*a1.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The bicarbonate ion is an amphoteric species that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH of the solution.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In organisms, carbonic acid production is catalysed by the enzyme known as carbonic anhydrase.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In addition to altering its acidity, the presence of carbon dioxide in water also affects its electrical properties.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in desalinated water, the electrical conductivity increases significantly from below 1 μS/cm to nearly 30 μS/cm.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] When heated, the water begins to gradually lose the conductivity induced by the presence of $\mathrm {CO_{2}}$ , especially noticeable as temperatures exceed 30 °C.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The temperature dependence of the electrical conductivity of fully deionized water without CO2 saturation is comparably low in relation to these data.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is a potent electrophile having an electrophilic reactivity that is comparable to benzaldehyde or strongly electrophilic α,β-unsaturated carbonyl compounds.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] However, unlike electrophiles of similar reactivity, the reactions of nucleophiles with CO2 are thermodynamically less favored and are often found to be highly reversible.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The reversible reaction of carbon dioxide with amines to make carbamates is used in CO2 scrubbers and has been suggested as a possible starting point for carbon capture and storage by amine gas treating.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In metal carbon dioxide complexes, CO2 serves as a ligand, which can facilitate the conversion of CO2 to other chemicals.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The redox potential for this reaction near pH 7 is about −0.53 V *versus* the standard hydrogen electrode.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The nickel-containing enzyme carbon monoxide dehydrogenase catalyses this process.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] At low concentrations, the gas is odorless; however, at sufficiently high concentrations, it has a sharp, acidic odor.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] At standard temperature and pressure, the density of carbon dioxide is around 1.98 kg/m3, about 1.53 times that of air.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] At a pressure of 1 atm (0.101325 MPa), the gas deposits directly to a solid at temperatures below 194.6855(30) K (−78.4645(30) °C) and the solid sublimes directly to a gas above this temperature.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In its solid state, carbon dioxide is commonly called dry ice.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Another form of solid carbon dioxide observed at high pressure is an amorphous glass-like solid.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This form of glass, called *carbonia*, is produced by supercooling heated CO2 at extreme pressures (40–48 GPa, or about 400,000 atmospheres) in a diamond anvil.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This discovery confirmed the theory that carbon dioxide could exist in a glass state similar to other members of its elemental family, like silicon dioxide (silica glass) and germanium dioxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Unlike silica and germania glasses, however, carbonia glass is not stable at normal pressures and reverts to gas when pressure is released.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] At temperatures and pressures above the critical point, carbon dioxide behaves as a supercritical fluid known as supercritical carbon dioxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is an end product of cellular respiration in organisms that obtain energy by breaking down sugars, fats and amino acids with oxygen as part of their metabolism.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This includes all plants, algae and animals and aerobic fungi and bacteria.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In vertebrates, the carbon dioxide travels in the blood from the body's tissues to the skin (e.g., amphibians) or the gills (e.g., fish), from where it dissolves in the water, or to the lungs from where it is exhaled.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] During active photosynthesis, plants can absorb more carbon dioxide from the atmosphere than they release in respiration.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Carbon fixation is a biochemical process by which atmospheric carbon dioxide is incorporated by plants, algae and cyanobacteria into energy-rich organic molecules such as glucose, thus creating their own food by photosynthesis.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Photosynthesis uses carbon dioxide and water to produce sugars from which other organic compounds can be constructed, and oxygen is produced as a by-product.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase oxygenase, commonly abbreviated to RuBisCO, is the enzyme involved in the first major step of carbon fixation, the production of two molecules of 3-phosphoglycerate from CO2 and ribulose bisphosphate, as shown in the diagram at left.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] RuBisCO is thought to be the single most abundant protein on Earth.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Phototrophs use the products of their photosynthesis as internal food sources and as raw material for the biosynthesis of more complex organic molecules, such as polysaccharides, nucleic acids, and proteins.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] These are used for their own growth, and also as the basis of the food chains and webs that feed other organisms, including animals such as ourselves.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Some important phototrophs, the coccolithophores synthesise hard calcium carbonate scales.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] A globally significant species of coccolithophore is *Emiliania huxleyi* whose calcite scales have formed the basis of many sedimentary rocks such as limestone, where what was previously atmospheric carbon can remain fixed for geological timescales.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Plants can grow as much as 50% faster in concentrations of 1,000 ppm CO2 when compared with ambient conditions, though this assumes no change in climate and no limitation on other nutrients.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Elevated CO2 levels cause increased growth reflected in the harvestable yield of crops, with wheat, rice and soybean all showing increases in yield of 12–14% under elevated CO2 in FACE experiments.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Increased atmospheric CO2 concentrations result in fewer stomata developing on plants which leads to reduced water usage and increased water-use efficiency.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Studies using FACE have shown that CO2 enrichment leads to decreased concentrations of micronutrients in crop plants.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This may have knock-on effects on other parts of ecosystems as herbivores will need to eat more food to gain the same amount of protein.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The concentration of secondary metabolites such as phenylpropanoids and flavonoids can also be altered in plants exposed to high concentrations of CO2.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Plants also emit CO2 during respiration, and so the majority of plants and algae, which use C3 photosynthesis, are only net absorbers during the day.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Though a growing forest will absorb many tons of CO2 each year, a mature forest will produce as much CO2 from respiration and decomposition of dead specimens (e.g., fallen branches) as is used in photosynthesis in growing plants.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Contrary to the long-standing view that they are carbon neutral, mature forests can continue to accumulate carbon and remain valuable carbon sinks, helping to maintain the carbon balance of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Additionally, and crucially to life on earth, photosynthesis by phytoplankton consumes dissolved CO2 in the upper ocean and thereby promotes the absorption of CO2 from the atmosphere.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide content in fresh air (averaged between sea-level and 10 kPa level, i.e., about 30 km (19 mi) altitude) varies between 0.036% (360 ppm) and 0.041% (412 ppm), depending on the location.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In humans, exposure to CO2 at concentrations greater than 5% causes the development of hypercapnia and respiratory acidosis.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of 7% to 10% (70,000 to 100,000 ppm) may cause suffocation, even in the presence of sufficient oxygen, manifesting as dizziness, headache, visual and hearing dysfunction, and unconsciousness within a few minutes to an hour.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of more than 10% may cause convulsions, coma, and death.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] CO2 levels of more than 30% act rapidly leading to loss of consciousness in seconds.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Carrion feeders attracted to the carcasses are then also killed.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Children have been killed in the same way near the city of Goma by CO2 emissions from the nearby volcano Mount Nyiragongo.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The Swahili term for this phenomenon is *mazuku*.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Adaptation to increased concentrations of CO2 occurs in humans, including modified breathing and kidney bicarbonate production, in order to balance the effects of blood acidification (acidosis).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Several studies suggested that 2.0 percent inspired concentrations could be used for closed air spaces (e.g. a submarine) since the adaptation is physiological and reversible, as deterioration in performance or in normal physical activity does not happen at this level of exposure for five days.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Yet, other studies show a decrease in cognitive function even at much lower levels.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Also, with ongoing respiratory acidosis, adaptation or compensatory mechanisms will be unable to reverse the condition.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] There are few studies of the health effects of long-term continuous CO2 exposure on humans and animals at levels below 1%.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Occupational CO2 exposure limits have been set in the United States at 0.5% (5000 ppm) for an eight-hour period.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] At this CO2 concentration, International Space Station crew experienced headaches, lethargy, mental slowness, emotional irritation, and sleep disruption.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Studies in animals at 0.5% CO2 have demonstrated kidney calcification and bone loss after eight weeks of exposure.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] A study of humans exposed in 2.5 hour sessions demonstrated significant negative effects on cognitive abilities at concentrations as low as 0.1% (1000 ppm) CO2 likely due to CO2 induced increases in cerebral blood flow.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Another study observed a decline in basic activity level and information usage at 1000 ppm, when compared to 500 ppm.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] However a review of the literature found that a reliable subset of studies on the phenomenon of carbon dioxide induced cognitive impairment to only show a small effect on high-level decision making (for concentrations below 5000 ppm).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Most of the studies were confounded by inadequate study designs, environmental comfort, uncertainties in exposure doses and differing cognitive assessments used.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Similarly a study on the effects of the concentration of CO2 in motorcycle helmets has been criticized for having dubious methodology in not noting the self-reports of motorcycle riders and taking measurements using mannequins.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Further when normal motorcycle conditions were achieved (such as highway or city speeds) or the visor was raised the concentration of CO2 declined to safe levels (0.2%).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Poor ventilation is one of the main causes of excessive CO2 concentrations in closed spaces, leading to poor indoor air quality.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide differential above outdoor concentrations at steady state conditions (when the occupancy and ventilation system operation are sufficiently long that CO2 concentration has stabilized) are sometimes used to estimate ventilation rates per person.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Higher CO2 concentrations are associated with occupant health, comfort and performance degradation.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] ASHRAE Standard 62.1–2007 ventilation rates may result in indoor concentrations up to 2,100 ppm above ambient outdoor conditions.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Thus if the outdoor concentration is 400 ppm, indoor concentrations may reach 2,500 ppm with ventilation rates that meet this industry consensus standard.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations in poorly ventilated spaces can be found even higher than this (range of 3,000 or 4,000 ppm).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Miners, who are particularly vulnerable to gas exposure due to insufficient ventilation, referred to mixtures of carbon dioxide and nitrogen as "blackdamp", "choke damp" or "stythe".
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Before more effective technologies were developed, miners would frequently monitor for dangerous levels of blackdamp and other gases in mine shafts by bringing a caged canary with them as they worked.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The canary is more sensitive to asphyxiant gases than humans, and as it became unconscious would stop singing and fall off its perch.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The Davy lamp could also detect high levels of blackdamp (which sinks, and collects near the floor) by burning less brightly, while methane, another suffocating gas and explosion risk, would make the lamp burn more brightly.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In February 2020, three people died from suffocation at a party in Moscow when dry ice (frozen CO2) was added to a swimming pool to cool it down.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] A similar accident occurred in 2018 when a woman died from CO2 fumes emanating from the large amount of dry ice she was transporting in her car.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Humans spend more and more time in a confined atmosphere (around 80-90% of the time in a building or vehicle).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In homes, schools, nurseries and offices, there are no systematic relationships between the levels of CO2 and other pollutants, and indoor CO2 is statistically not a good predictor of pollutants linked to outdoor road (or air, etc.) traffic.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is the parameter that changes the fastest (with hygrometry and oxygen levels when humans or animals are gathered in a closed or poorly ventilated room).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In poor countries, many open hearths are sources of CO2 and CO emitted directly into the living environment.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Local concentrations of carbon dioxide can reach high values near strong sources, especially those that are isolated by surrounding terrain.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] At the Bossoleto hot spring near Rapolano Terme in Tuscany, Italy, situated in a bowl-shaped depression about 100 m (330 ft) in diameter, concentrations of CO2 rise to above 75% overnight, sufficient to kill insects and small animals.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] After sunrise the gas is dispersed by convection.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] High concentrations of CO2 produced by disturbance of deep lake water saturated with CO2 are thought to have caused 37 fatalities at Lake Monoun, Cameroon in 1984 and 1700 casualties at Lake Nyos, Cameroon in 1986.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The body produces approximately 2.3 pounds (1.0 kg) of carbon dioxide per day per person, containing 0.63 pounds (290 g) of carbon.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In humans, this carbon dioxide is carried through the venous system and is breathed out through the lungs, resulting in lower concentrations in the arteries.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The carbon dioxide content of the blood is often given as the partial pressure, which is the pressure which carbon dioxide would have had if it alone occupied the volume.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In humans, the blood carbon dioxide contents are shown in the adjacent table.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is carried in blood in three different ways.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Exact percentages vary between arterial and venous blood.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Hemoglobin, the main oxygen-carrying molecule in red blood cells, carries both oxygen and carbon dioxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] However, the CO2 bound to hemoglobin does not bind to the same site as oxygen.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Instead, it combines with the N-terminal groups on the four globin chains.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] However, because of allosteric effects on the hemoglobin molecule, the binding of CO2 decreases the amount of oxygen that is bound for a given partial pressure of oxygen.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This is known as the Haldane Effect, and is important in the transport of carbon dioxide from the tissues to the lungs.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Conversely, a rise in the partial pressure of CO2 or a lower pH will cause offloading of oxygen from hemoglobin, which is known as the Bohr effect.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is one of the mediators of local autoregulation of blood supply.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] If its concentration is high, the capillaries expand to allow a greater blood flow to that tissue.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Bicarbonate ions are crucial for regulating blood pH.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] A person's breathing rate influences the level of CO2 in their blood.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Breathing that is too slow or shallow causes respiratory acidosis, while breathing that is too rapid leads to hyperventilation, which can cause respiratory alkalosis.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Although the body requires oxygen for metabolism, low oxygen levels normally do not stimulate breathing.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Rather, breathing is stimulated by higher carbon dioxide levels.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] As a result, breathing low-pressure air or a gas mixture with no oxygen at all (such as pure nitrogen) can lead to loss of consciousness without ever experiencing air hunger.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This is especially perilous for high-altitude fighter pilots.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] It is also why flight attendants instruct passengers, in case of loss of cabin pressure, to apply the oxygen mask to themselves first before helping others; otherwise, one risks losing consciousness.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The respiratory centers try to maintain an arterial CO2 pressure of 40 mmHg.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] With intentional hyperventilation, the CO2 content of arterial blood may be lowered to 10–20 mmHg (the oxygen content of the blood is little affected), and the respiratory drive is diminished.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This is why one can hold one's breath longer after hyperventilating than without hyperventilating.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This carries the risk that unconsciousness may result before the need to breathe becomes overwhelming, which is why hyperventilation is particularly dangerous before free diving.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In the atmosphere of Earth, carbon dioxide (CO2) is a trace gas that plays an integral part in the greenhouse effect, carbon cycle, photosynthesis, and oceanic carbon cycle.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] It is one of three main greenhouse gases in the atmosphere of Earth.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] In 2026, the concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere reached 432 ppm or 0.0432% (on a molar basis), representing a mass of 3380 gigatonnes.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This is an increase of 54% since the start of the Industrial Revolution, up from 280 ppm during the 10,000 years prior to the mid-18th century.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The current increase in CO2 concentrations is primarily driven by the burning of fossil fuels.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Other significant human activities that emit CO2 include cement production, deforestation, and biomass burning.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 and other long-lived greenhouse gases such as methane increase the absorption and emission of infrared radiation by the atmosphere.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This has led to a rise in average global temperature and ocean acidification.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Another direct effect is the CO2 fertilization effect.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 causes a range of further effects of climate change on the environment and human living conditions.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] It absorbs and emits infrared radiation at its two infrared-active vibrational frequencies.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The two wavelengths are 4.26 μm (2,347 cm−1) (antisymmetric stretching vibrational mode) and 14.99 μm (667 cm−1) (bending vibrational mode).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] CO2 plays a significant role in influencing Earth's surface temperature through the greenhouse effect.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Light emission from the Earth's surface is most intense in the infrared region between 200 and 2500 cm−1, as opposed to light emission from the much hotter Sun which is most intense in the visible region.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Absorption of infrared light at the vibrational frequencies of atmospheric CO2 traps energy near the surface, warming the surface of Earth and its lower atmosphere.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Less energy reaches the upper atmosphere, which is therefore cooler because of this absorption.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The present atmospheric concentration of CO2 is the highest for 14 million years.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of CO2 in the atmosphere were as high as 4,000 ppm during the Cambrian period about 500 million years ago, and as low as 180 ppm during the Quaternary glaciation of the last two million years.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Reconstructed temperature records for the last 420 million years indicate that atmospheric CO2 concentrations peaked at approximately 2,000 ppm.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This peak happened during the Devonian period (400 million years ago).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Another peak occurred in the Triassic period (220–200 million years ago).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide dissolves in the ocean to form carbonic acid (H2CO3), bicarbonate (HCO3–), and carbonate (CO32–).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] There is about fifty times as much carbon dioxide dissolved in the oceans as exists in the atmosphere.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The oceans act as an enormous carbon sink, and have taken up about a third of CO2 emitted by human activity.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Ocean acidification is the ongoing decrease in the pH of the Earth's ocean.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Between 1950 and 2020, the average pH of the ocean surface fell from approximately 8.15 to 8.05.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide emissions from human activities are the primary cause of ocean acidification, with atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO2) levels exceeding 422 ppm (as of 2024).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] CO2 from the atmosphere is absorbed by the oceans.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This chemical reaction produces carbonic acid (H2CO3) which dissociates into a bicarbonate ion (HCO−3) and a hydrogen ion (H+).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The presence of free hydrogen ions (H+) lowers the pH of the ocean, increasing acidity (this does not mean that seawater is acidic yet; it is still alkaline, with a pH higher than 8).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Marine calcifying organisms, such as mollusks and corals, are especially vulnerable because they rely on calcium carbonate to build shells and skeletons.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] A change in pH by 0.1 represents a 26% increase in hydrogen ion concentration in the world's oceans (the pH scale is logarithmic, so a change of one in pH units is equivalent to a tenfold change in hydrogen ion concentration).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Sea-surface pH and carbonate saturation states vary depending on ocean depth and location.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Colder and higher latitude waters are capable of absorbing more CO2.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This can cause acidity to rise, lowering the pH and carbonate saturation levels in these areas.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Several other factors influence the atmosphere-ocean CO2 exchange, and thus local ocean acidification.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] These include ocean currents and upwelling zones, proximity to large continental rivers, sea ice coverage, and atmospheric exchange with nitrogen and sulfur from fossil fuel burning and agriculture.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Changes in ocean chemistry can have extensive direct and indirect effects on organisms and their habitats.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] One of the most important repercussions of increasing ocean acidity relates to the production of shells out of calcium carbonate (CaCO3).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] This process is called calcification and is important to the biology and survival of a wide range of marine organisms.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Calcification involves the precipitation of dissolved ions into solid CaCO3 structures, structures for many marine organisms, such as coccolithophores, foraminifera, crustaceans, mollusks, etc.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] After they are formed, these CaCO3 structures are vulnerable to dissolution unless the surrounding seawater contains saturating concentrations of carbonate ions (CO2−3).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Very little of the extra carbon dioxide that is added into the ocean remains as dissolved carbon dioxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The majority dissociates into additional bicarbonate and free hydrogen ions.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] To maintain chemical equilibrium, some of the carbonate ions already in the ocean combine with some of the hydrogen ions to make further bicarbonate.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is also introduced into the oceans through hydrothermal vents.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The *Champagne* hydrothermal vent, found at the Northwest Eifuku volcano in the Mariana Trench, produces almost pure liquid carbon dioxide, one of only two known sites in the world as of 2004, the other being in the Okinawa Trough.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-dioxide] The finding of a submarine lake of liquid carbon dioxide in the Okinawa Trough was reported in 2006.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The most common source of carbon monoxide is the partial combustion of carbon-containing compounds.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Numerous environmental and biological sources generate carbon monoxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In industry, carbon monoxide is important in the production of many compounds, including drugs, fragrances, and fuels.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] CO is one of the most acutely toxic contaminants affecting indoor air quality.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] CO may be emitted from tobacco smoke and generated from malfunctioning fuel-burning stoves (wood, kerosene, natural gas, propane) and fuel-burning heating systems (wood, oil, natural gas) and from blocked flues connected to these appliances.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide poisoning is the most common type of fatal air poisoning in many countries.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide has important biological roles across biological kingdoms.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] It is produced by many organisms, including humans.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In mammalian physiology, carbon monoxide is a classical example of hormesis where low concentrations serve as an endogenous neurotransmitter (gasotransmitter) and high concentrations are toxic, resulting in carbon monoxide poisoning.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] It is isoelectronic with both cyanide anion CN− and molecular nitrogen N2.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is the simplest oxocarbon and is isoelectronic with other triply bonded diatomic species possessing 10 valence electrons, including the cyanide anion, the nitrosonium cation, boron monofluoride and molecular nitrogen.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] It has a molar mass of 28.0, which, according to the ideal gas law, makes it slightly less dense than air, whose average molar mass is 28.8.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The carbon and oxygen are connected by a triple bond that consists of a net two pi bonds and one sigma bond.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The bond length between the carbon atom and the oxygen atom is 112.8 pm.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] This bond length is consistent with a triple bond, as in molecular nitrogen (N2), which has a similar bond length (109.76 pm) and nearly the same molecular mass.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon–oxygen double bonds are significantly longer, 120.8 pm in formaldehyde, for example.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The boiling point (82 K) and melting point (68 K) are very similar to those of N2 (77 K and 63 K, respectively).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The bond-dissociation energy of 1072 kJ/mol is stronger than that of N2 (942 kJ/mol) and represents the strongest chemical bond known.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The ground electronic state of carbon monoxide is a singlet state, since there are no unpaired electrons.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The strength of the C≡O bond in carbon monoxide is indicated by the high frequency of its vibration, 2143 cm−1.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] For comparison, organic carbonyls such as ketones and esters absorb at around 1700 cm−1.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon and oxygen together have a total of 10 electrons in the valence shell.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Following the octet rule for both carbon and oxygen, the two atoms form a triple bond, with six shared electrons in three bonding molecular orbitals, rather than the usual double bond found in organic carbonyl compounds.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Since four of the shared electrons come from the oxygen atom and only two from carbon, one bonding orbital is occupied by two electrons from oxygen, forming a dative or dipolar bond.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] This causes a C←O polarization of the molecule, with a small negative charge on carbon and a small positive charge on oxygen.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The other two bonding orbitals are each occupied by one electron from carbon and one from oxygen, forming (polar) covalent bonds with a reverse C→O polarization since oxygen is more electronegative than carbon.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In the free carbon monoxide molecule, a net negative charge δ− remains at the carbon end and the molecule has a small dipole moment of 0.122 D.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The molecule is therefore asymmetric: oxygen is more electron dense than carbon and is also slightly positively charged, unlike the negative carbon.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide has a computed fractional bond order of 2.6, indicating that the "third" bond is important but constitutes somewhat less than a full bond.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Thus, in valence bond terms, −C≡O+ is the most important structure, while :C=O is non-octet, but has a neutral formal charge on each atom and represents the second most important resonance contributor.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Because of the lone pair and divalence of carbon in this resonance structure, carbon monoxide is often considered to be an extraordinarily stabilized carbene.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Isocyanides are compounds in which the O is replaced by an NR (R = alkyl or aryl) group and have a similar bonding scheme.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] If carbon monoxide acts as a ligand, the polarity of the dipole may reverse with a net negative charge on the oxygen end, depending on the structure of the coordination complex.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] See also the section *"Coordination chemistry"* below.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Theoretical and experimental studies show that, despite the greater electronegativity of oxygen, the dipole moment points from the more-negative carbon end to the more-positive oxygen end.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The three bonds are in fact polar covalent bonds that are strongly polarized.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The calculated polarization toward the oxygen atom is 71% for the σ-bond and 77% for both π-bonds.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The oxidation state of carbon in carbon monoxide is +2 in each of these structures.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] It is calculated by counting all the bonding electrons as belonging to the more electronegative oxygen.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Only the two non-bonding electrons on carbon are assigned to carbon.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In this count, carbon then has only two valence electrons in the molecule, versus four in the free atom.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide occurs in many environments, usually in trace levels.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Photochemical degradation of plant matter, for example, generates an estimated 60 million tons/year.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide (CO) is present in small amounts (about 80 ppb) in the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Most comes from chemical reactions with organic compounds emitted by human activities and natural origins due to photochemical reactions in the troposphere that generate about 5 × 1012 kilograms per year.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Other natural sources of CO include volcanoes, forest and bushfires, and other miscellaneous forms of combustion such as fossil fuels.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Small amounts are also emitted from the ocean, and from geological activity because carbon monoxide occurs dissolved in molten volcanic rock at high pressures in the Earth's mantle.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Because natural sources of carbon monoxide vary from year to year, it is difficult to accurately measure natural emissions of the gas.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide has an indirect effect on radiative forcing by elevating concentrations of direct greenhouse gases, including methane and tropospheric ozone.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] CO can react chemically with other atmospheric constituents (primarily the hydroxyl radical, •OH) that would otherwise destroy methane.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Through natural processes in the atmosphere, it is oxidized to carbon dioxide and ozone.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is short-lived in the atmosphere (with an average lifetime of about one to two months), and spatially variable in concentration.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Due to its long lifetime in the mid-troposphere, carbon monoxide is also used as a tracer for pollutant plumes.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Beyond Earth, carbon monoxide is the second-most common diatomic molecule in the interstellar medium, after molecular hydrogen.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Because of its asymmetry, this polar molecule produces far brighter spectral lines than the hydrogen molecule, making CO much easier to detect.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Interstellar CO was first detected with radio telescopes in 1970.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] It is now the most commonly used tracer of molecular gas in general in the interstellar medium of galaxies, as molecular hydrogen can only be detected using ultraviolet light, which requires space telescopes.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide observations provide much of the information about the molecular clouds in which most stars form.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Beta Pictoris, the second brightest star in the constellation Pictor, shows an excess of infrared emission compared to normal stars of its type, which is caused by large quantities of dust and gas (including carbon monoxide) near the star.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In the atmosphere of Venus carbon monoxide occurs as a result of the photodissociation of carbon dioxide by electromagnetic radiation of wavelengths shorter than 169 nm.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] It has also been identified spectroscopically on the surface of Neptune's moon Triton.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Solid carbon monoxide is a component of comets.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The volatile or "ice" component of Halley's Comet is about 15% CO.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] At room temperature and at normal atmospheric pressure, carbon monoxide is merely metastable (see Boudouard reaction) and the same is true at low temperatures where CO and CO2 are solid, but nevertheless it can exist for billions of years in comets.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] There is very little CO in the atmosphere of Pluto, which seems to have been formed from comets.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] This may be because there is (or was) liquid water inside Pluto.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] This is called the water-gas shift reaction when occurring in the gas phase, but it can also take place (very slowly) in an aqueous solution.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] These reactions can take place in a few million years even at temperatures such as found on Pluto.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Large CO pollution events can be observed from space over cities.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Along with aldehydes, carbon monoxide is part of the series of cycles of chemical reactions that form photochemical smog.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] It reacts with hydroxyl radical (•OH) to produce a radical intermediate •HOCO, which rapidly transfers its radical hydrogen to O2 to form peroxy radical (HO2•) and carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Peroxy radical subsequently reacts with nitrogen oxide (NO) to form nitrogen dioxide (NO2) and hydroxyl radical.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] NO2 gives O(3P) via photolysis, thereby forming O3 following reaction with O2.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Although the creation of NO2 is the critical step leading to low-level ozone formation, it also increases this ozone in another, somewhat mutually exclusive way, by reducing the quantity of NO that is available to react with ozone.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is one of the most acutely toxic indoor air contaminants.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide may be emitted from tobacco smoke and generated from malfunctioning fuel burning stoves (wood, kerosene, natural gas, propane) and fuel burning heating systems (wood, oil, natural gas) and from blocked flues connected to these appliances.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In developed countries, the main sources of indoor CO emission come from cooking and heating devices that burn fossil fuels and are faulty, incorrectly installed, or poorly maintained.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Appliance malfunction may be due to faulty installation or lack of maintenance and proper use.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In low- and middle-income countries the most common sources of CO in homes are burning biomass fuels and cigarette smoke.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Miners refer to carbon monoxide as "whitedamp" or the "silent killer".
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] It can be found in confined areas of poor ventilation in both surface mines and underground mines.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The most common sources of carbon monoxide in mining operations are the internal combustion engine and explosives; however, in coal mines, carbon monoxide can also be found due to the low-temperature oxidation of coal.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The idiom "Canary in the coal mine" pertained to an early warning of a carbon monoxide presence.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Acute exposure can also lead to long-term neurological effects such as cognitive and behavioural changes.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Severe CO poisoning may lead to unconsciousness, coma, and death.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Chronic exposure to low concentrations of carbon monoxide may lead to lethargy, headaches, nausea, flu-like symptoms, and neuropsychological and cardiovascular issues.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide has a wide range of functions across all disciplines of chemistry.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The four premier categories of reactivity involve metal-carbonyl catalysis, radical chemistry, cation and anion chemistries.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Most metals form coordination complexes containing covalently attached carbon monoxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] These derivatives, called metal carbonyls, tend to be more robust when the metal is in lower oxidation states.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] For example, iron pentacarbonyl (Fe(CO)5) is an air-stable, distillable liquid.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] These volatile complexes are often highly toxic.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Some metal–CO complexes are prepared by decarbonylation of organic solvents, not from CO.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] For instance, iridium trichloride and triphenylphosphine react in boiling 2-methoxyethanol or DMF to afford IrCl(CO)(PPh3)2.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] As a ligand, CO binds through carbon, forming a kind of triple bond.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The lone pair on the carbon atom donates electron density to form a M-CO sigma bond.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The two π* orbitals on CO bind to filled metal orbitals.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The effect is related to the Dewar-Chatt-Duncanson model.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The effects of the quasi-triple M-C bond is reflected in the infrared spectrum of these complexes.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Whereas free CO vibrates at 2143 cm−1, its complexes tend to absorb near 1950 cm−1.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In the presence of strong acids, alkenes react with carboxylic acids.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Hydrolysis of this species (an acylium ion) gives the carboxylic acid, a net process known as the Koch–Haaf reaction.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In the Gattermann–Koch reaction, arenes are converted to benzaldehyde derivatives in the presence of CO, AlCl3, and HCl.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] A mixture of hydrogen gas and CO reacts with alkenes to give aldehydes.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The process requires the presence of metal catalysts.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] With main group reagents, CO undergoes several noteworthy reactions.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Chlorination of CO is the industrial route to the important compound phosgene.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] With borane CO forms the adduct H3BCO, which is isoelectronic with the acylium cation [H3CCO]+.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] CO reacts with sodium to give products resulting from C−C coupling such as sodium acetylenediolate 2Na+·C2O2−2.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] It reacts with molten potassium to give a mixture of an organometallic compound, potassium acetylenediolate 2K+·C2O2−2, potassium benzenehexolate 6K+·C6O6−6, and potassium rhodizonate 2K+·C6O2−6.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The compounds cyclohexanehexone or triquinoyl (C6O6) and cyclopentanepentone or leuconic acid (C5O5), which so far have been obtained only in trace amounts, can be regarded as polymers of carbon monoxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] At pressures exceeding 5 GPa, carbon monoxide converts to polycarbonyl, a solid polymer that is metastable at atmospheric pressure but is explosive.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is conveniently produced in the laboratory by the dehydration of formic acid or oxalic acid, for example with concentrated sulfuric acid.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Thermal combustion is the most common source for carbon monoxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Many methods have been developed for carbon monoxide production.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] A major industrial source of CO is producer gas, a mixture containing mostly carbon monoxide and nitrogen, formed by combustion of carbon in air at high temperature when there is an excess of carbon.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In an oven, air is passed through a bed of coke.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The initially produced CO2 equilibrates with the remaining hot carbon to give CO.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The reaction of CO2 with carbon to give CO is described as the Boudouard reaction.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Other similar "synthesis gases" can be obtained from natural gas and other fuels.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide can also be produced by high-temperature electrolysis of carbon dioxide with solid oxide electrolyzer cells.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] One method developed at DTU Energy uses a cerium oxide catalyst and does not have any issues of fouling of the catalyst.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is also produced by the direct oxidation of carbon in a limited supply of oxygen or air.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Since CO is a gas, the reduction process can be driven by heating, exploiting the positive (favorable) entropy of reaction.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The Ellingham diagram shows that CO formation is favored over CO2 in high temperatures.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is an industrial gas with many applications in bulk chemicals manufacturing.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Large quantities of aldehydes are produced by the hydroformylation reaction of alkenes, carbon monoxide, and H2.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Hydroformylation is coupled to the Shell higher olefin process to give precursors to detergents.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Phosgene, useful for preparing isocyanates, polycarbonates, and polyurethanes, is produced by passing purified carbon monoxide and chlorine gas through a bed of porous activated carbon, which serves as a catalyst.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] World production of this compound was estimated to be 2.74 million tonnes in 1989.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Methanol is produced by the hydrogenation of carbon monoxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In a related reaction, the hydrogenation of carbon monoxide is coupled to C−C bond formation, as in the Fischer–Tropsch process where carbon monoxide is hydrogenated to liquid hydrocarbon fuels.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] This technology allows coal or biomass to be converted to diesel.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In the Cativa process, carbon monoxide and methanol react in the presence of a homogeneous iridium catalyst and hydroiodic acid to give acetic acid.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] This process is responsible for most of the industrial production of acetic acid.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is a strong reductive agent and has been used in pyrometallurgy to reduce metals from ores since ancient times.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide strips oxygen off metal oxides, reducing them to pure metal in high temperatures and forming carbon dioxide in the process.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is not usually supplied as is, in the gaseous phase, in the reactor, but rather it is formed in high temperature in presence of oxygen-carrying ore, or a carboniferous agent such as coke, and high temperature.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The blast furnace process is a typical example of a process of reduction of metal from ore with carbon monoxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Likewise, blast furnace gas collected at the top of blast furnaces still contains some 10% to 30% of carbon monoxide, and is used as fuel on Cowper stoves and on Siemens-Martin furnaces on open hearth steelmaking.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide has been proposed for use as a fuel on Mars by NASA researcher Geoffrey Landis.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Landis also proposed manufacturing the fuel from the similar carbon dioxide atmosphere of Venus for a sample return mission, in combination with solar-powered UAVs and rocket balloon ascent.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is used in electrochemistry to study the structure of electrodes thanks to its strong affinity to some metals used as electrocatalysts, through a technique known as CO stripping.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is a bioactive molecule which acts as a gaseous signaling molecule.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] It is naturally produced by many enzymatic and non-enzymatic pathways, the best understood of which is the catabolic action of heme oxygenase on the heme derived from hemoproteins such as hemoglobin.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Following the first report that carbon monoxide is a normal neurotransmitter in 1993, carbon monoxide has received significant clinical attention as a biological regulator.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Because of carbon monoxide's role in the body, abnormalities in its metabolism have been linked to a variety of diseases, including neurodegenerations, hypertension, heart failure, and pathological inflammation.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In many tissues, carbon monoxide acts as anti-inflammatory, vasodilatory, and encouragers of neovascular growth.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In animal model studies, carbon monoxide reduced the severity of experimentally induced bacterial sepsis, pancreatitis, hepatic ischemia/reperfusion injury, colitis, osteoarthritis, lung injury, lung transplantation rejection, and neuropathic pain while promoting skin wound healing.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Therefore, there is significant interest in the therapeutic potential of carbon monoxide becoming pharmaceutical agent and clinical standard of care.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Many laboratories worldwide have studied carbon monoxide for its anti-inflammatory and cytoprotective properties.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] These properties might be usable for preventing the development of a series of pathological conditions including ischemia reperfusion injury, transplant rejection, atherosclerosis, severe sepsis, severe malaria, or autoimmunity.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Many pharmaceutical drug delivery initiatives have developed methods to safely administer carbon monoxide, and subsequent controlled clinical trials have evaluated the therapeutic effect of carbon monoxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Microbiota may also utilize carbon monoxide as a gasotransmitter.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide sensing is a signaling pathway facilitated by proteins such as CooA.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The scope of the biological roles for carbon monoxide sensing is still unknown.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The human microbiome produces, consumes, and responds to carbon monoxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] For example, in certain bacteria, carbon monoxide is produced via the reduction of carbon dioxide by the enzyme carbon monoxide dehydrogenase with favorable bioenergetics to power downstream cellular operations.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In another example, carbon monoxide is a nutrient for methanogenic archaea which reduce it to methane using hydrogen.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide has certain antimicrobial properties which have been studied to treat against infectious diseases.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is used in modified atmosphere packaging systems in the US, mainly with fresh meat products such as beef, pork, and fish to keep them looking fresh.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The benefit is two-fold: carbon monoxide protects against microbial spoilage and enhances the meat color for consumer appeal.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The carbon monoxide combines with myoglobin to form carboxymyoglobin, a bright-cherry-red pigment.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carboxymyoglobin is more stable than the oxygenated form of myoglobin, oxymyoglobin, which can become oxidized to the brown pigment metmyoglobin.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] This stable red color can persist much longer than in normally packaged meat.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Typical levels of carbon monoxide used in the facilities that use this process are between 0.4% and 0.5%.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The technology was first given "generally recognized as safe" (GRAS) status by the U.S.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) in 2002 for use as a secondary packaging system, and requires no labeling.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In 2004, the FDA approved CO as primary packaging method, declaring that CO does not mask spoilage odor.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The process is currently unauthorized in many other countries, including Japan, Singapore, and the European Union.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In ancient history, Hannibal executed Roman prisoners with coal fumes during the Second Punic War.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide was used for genocide during the Holocaust at some extermination camps, the most notable by gas vans in Chełmno, and in the Action T4 "euthanasia" program.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Man has maintained a complex relationship with carbon monoxide since first learning to control fire circa 800,000 BC.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Early man probably discovered the toxicity of carbon monoxide poisoning upon introducing fire into his dwellings.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The early development of metallurgy and smelting technologies emerging circa 6,000 BC through the Bronze Age likewise plagued man from carbon monoxide exposure.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Apart from the toxicity of carbon monoxide, Native Americans in the United States may have experienced the neuroactive properties of carbon monoxide through shamanistic fireside rituals.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Early civilizations developed mythological tales to explain the origin of fire, such as Prometheus from Greek mythology who shared fire with humans.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Aristotle (384–322 BC) first recorded that burning coals produced toxic fumes.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Greek physician Galen (AD 129–199) speculated that there was a change in the composition of the air that caused harm when inhaled, and many others of the era developed a basis of knowledge about carbon monoxide in the context of coal fume toxicity.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Cleopatra may have died from carbon monoxide poisoning.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In 1697, Georg Ernst Stahl used *carbonarii halitus* to refer to toxic vapors thought to be carbon monoxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Friedrich Hoffmann conducted the first modern scientific investigation into carbon monoxide poisoning from coal in 1716.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Herman Boerhaave conducted the first scientific experiments on the effect of carbon monoxide (coal fumes) on animals in the 1730s.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Joseph Priestley is considered to have first synthesized carbon monoxide in 1772.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carl Wilhelm Scheele similarly isolated carbon monoxide from charcoal in 1773 and thought it could be the carbonic entity making fumes toxic.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Torbern Bergman isolated carbon monoxide from oxalic acid in 1775.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] One year later, the French chemist de Lassone produced CO by heating zinc oxide with coke, but mistakenly identified the gaseous product as hydrogen, as it burned with a blue flame.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In the presence of oxygen, including atmospheric concentrations, carbon monoxide burns with a blue flame, producing carbon dioxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Antoine Lavoisier conducted similarly inconclusive experiments in 1777.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The gas was identified as a compound containing carbon and oxygen by William Cruickshank in 1800.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Thomas Beddoes and James Watt recognized carbon monoxide (as hydrocarbonate) to brighten venous blood in 1793.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Watt suggested coal fumes could act as an antidote to the oxygen in blood, and Beddoes and Watt likewise suggested hydrocarbonate has a greater affinity for animal fiber than oxygen in 1796.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In 1854, Adrien Chenot similarly suggested carbon monoxide to remove the oxygen from blood and then be oxidized by the body to carbon dioxide.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] The mechanism for carbon monoxide poisoning is widely credited to Claude Bernard whose memoirs beginning in 1846 and published in 1857 phrased, "prevents arterials blood from becoming venous".
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Felix Hoppe-Seyler independently published similar conclusions in the following year.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide gained recognition as an essential reagent in the 1900s.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Three industrial processes illustrate its evolution in industry.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In the Fischer–Tropsch process, coal and related carbon-rich feedstocks are converted into liquid fuels via the intermediacy of CO.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Developed as part of the German war effort to compensate for their lack of domestic petroleum, this technology continues today.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Also in Germany, a mixture of CO and hydrogen was found to combine with olefins to give aldehydes.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] This process, called hydroformylation, is used to produce many large scale chemicals such as surfactants as well as specialty compounds that are popular fragrances and drugs.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] For example, CO is used in the production of vitamin A.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] In a third major process, attributed to researchers at Monsanto, CO combines with methanol to give acetic acid.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Most acetic acid is produced by the Cativa process.
[src:bioconversion/carbon-monoxide] Hydroformylation and the acetic acid syntheses are two of myriad carbonylation processes.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Interest in cellulosic ethanol is driven by its potential to replace ethanol made from corn or sugarcane.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Since these plants are also used for food products, diverting them for ethanol production can cause food prices to rise; cellulose-based sources, on the other hand, generally do not compete with food, since the fibrous parts of plants are mostly inedible to humans.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Another potential advantage is the high diversity and abundance of cellulose sources; grasses, trees and algae are found in almost every environment on Earth.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Even municipal solid waste components like paper could conceivably be made into ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The main current disadvantage of cellulosic ethanol is its high cost of production, which is more complex and requires more steps than corn-based or sugarcane-based ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Cellulosic ethanol received significant attention in the 2000s and early 2010s.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The United States government in particular funded research into its commercialization and set targets for the proportion of cellulosic ethanol added to vehicle fuel.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] A large number of new companies specializing in cellulosic ethanol, in addition to many existing companies, invested in pilot-scale production plants.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] However, the much cheaper manufacturing of grain-based ethanol, along with the low price of oil in the 2010s, meant that cellulosic ethanol was not competitive with these established fuels.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] As a result, most of the new refineries were closed by the mid-2010s and many of the newly founded companies became insolvent.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] A few still exist, but are mainly used for demonstration or research purposes; as of 2021, none produces cellulosic ethanol at scale.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Cellulosic ethanol is a type of biofuel produced from lignocellulose, a structural material that comprises much of the mass of plants and is composed mainly of cellulose, hemicellulose and lignin.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Popular sources of lignocellulose include both agricultural waste products (e.g. corn stover or wood chips) and grasses like switchgrass and *miscanthus* species.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] These raw materials for ethanol production have the advantage of being abundant and diverse and would not compete with food production, unlike the more commonly used corn and cane sugars.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] However, they also require more processing to make the sugar monomers available to the microorganisms typically used to produce ethanol by fermentation, which drives up the price of cellulose-derived ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Cellulosic ethanol can reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 85% over reformulated gasoline.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] By contrast, starch ethanol (e.g., from corn), which most frequently uses natural gas to provide energy for the process, may not reduce greenhouse gas emissions at all depending on how the starch-based feedstock is produced.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] According to the National Academy of Sciences in 2011, there is no commercially viable bio-refinery in existence to convert lignocellulosic biomass to fuel.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The French chemist Henri Braconnot was the first to discover that cellulose could be hydrolyzed into sugars by treatment with sulfuric acid in 1819.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The hydrolyzed sugar could then be processed to form ethanol through fermentation.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The first commercialized ethanol production began in Germany in 1898, where acid was used to hydrolyze cellulose.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In the United States, the Standard Alcohol Company opened the first cellulosic ethanol production plant in South Carolina in 1910.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Later, a second plant was opened in Louisiana.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] However, both plants were closed after World War I due to economic reasons.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The first attempt at commercializing a process for ethanol from wood was done in Germany in 1898.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] It involved the use of dilute acid to hydrolyze the cellulose to glucose, and was able to produce 7.6 liters of ethanol per 100 kg of wood waste (18 US gal (68 L) per ton).
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The Germans soon developed an industrial process optimized for yields of around 50 US gallons (190 L) per ton of biomass.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] This process soon found its way to the US, culminating in two commercial plants operating in the southeast during World War I.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] These plants used what was called "the American Process" — a one-stage dilute sulfuric acid hydrolysis.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Though the yields were half that of the original German process (25 US gallons (95 L) of ethanol per ton versus 50), the throughput of the American process was much higher.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] A drop in lumber production forced the plants to close shortly after the end of World War I.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In the meantime, a small but steady amount of research on dilute acid hydrolysis continued at the USFS's Forest Products Laboratory.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] During World War II, the US again turned to cellulosic ethanol, this time for conversion to butadiene to produce synthetic rubber.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The Vulcan Copper and Supply Company was contracted to construct and operate a plant to convert sawdust into ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The plant was based on modifications to the original German Scholler process as developed by the Forest Products Laboratory.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] This plant achieved an ethanol yield of 50 US gal (190 L) per dry ton, but was still not profitable and was closed after the war.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] With the rapid development of enzyme technologies in the last two decades, the acid hydrolysis process has gradually been replaced by enzymatic hydrolysis.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Chemical pretreatment of the feedstock is required to hydrolyze (separate) hemicellulose, so it can be more effectively converted into sugars.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The dilute acid pretreatment is developed based on the early work on acid hydrolysis of wood at the USFS's Forest Products Laboratory.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In 2009, the Forest Products Laboratory together with the University of Wisconsin–Madison developed a sulfite pretreatment to overcome the recalcitrance of lignocellulose for robust enzymatic hydrolysis of wood cellulose.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In his 2007 State of the Union Address on January 23, 2007, US President George W.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Bush announced a proposed mandate for 35 billion US gallons (130×10^9 L) of ethanol by 2017.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Later that year, the US Department of Energy awarded $385 million in grants aimed at jump-starting ethanol production from nontraditional sources like wood chips, switchgrass, and citrus peels.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In 2010, a genetically engineered yeast strain was developed to produce its own cellulose-digesting enzymes.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Assuming this technology can be scaled to industrial levels, it would eliminate one or more steps of cellulolysis, reducing both the time required and costs of production.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Although lignocellulose is the most abundant plant material resource, its usability is curtailed by its rigid structure.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] As a result, an effective pretreatment is needed to liberate the cellulose from the lignin seal and its crystalline structure so as to render it accessible for a subsequent hydrolysis step.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] By far, most pretreatments are done through physical or chemical means.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] To achieve higher efficiency, both physical and chemical pretreatments are required.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Physical pretreatment involves reducing biomass particle size by mechanical processing methods such as milling or extrusion.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Chemical pretreatment partially depolymerizes the lignocellulose so enzymes can access the cellulose for microbial reactions.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Chemical pretreatment techniques include acid hydrolysis, steam explosion, ammonia fiber expansion, organosolv, sulfite pretreatment, SO2-ethanol-water fractionation, alkaline wet oxidation and ozone pretreatment.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Besides effective cellulose liberation, an ideal pretreatment has to minimize the formation of degradation products because they can inhibit the subsequent hydrolysis and fermentation steps.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The presence of inhibitors further complicates and increases the cost of ethanol production due to required detoxification steps.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] For instance, even though acid hydrolysis is probably the oldest and most-studied pretreatment technique, it produces several potent inhibitors including furfural and hydroxymethylfurfural.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Ammonia Fiber Expansion (AFEX) is an example of a promising pretreatment that produces no inhibitors.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Most pretreatment processes are not effective when applied to feedstocks with high lignin content, such as forest biomass.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] These require alternative or specialized approaches.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Organosolv, SPORL ('sulfite pretreatment to overcome recalcitrance of lignocellulose') and SO2-ethanol-water (AVAP®) processes are the three processes that can achieve over 90% cellulose conversion for forest biomass, especially those of softwood species.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] SPORL is the most energy efficient (sugar production per unit energy consumption in pretreatment) and robust process for pretreatment of forest biomass with very low production of fermentation inhibitors.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Organosolv pulping is particularly effective for hardwoods and offers easy recovery of a hydrophobic lignin product by dilution and precipitation.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] AVAP® process effectively fractionates all types of lignocellulosics into clean highly digestible cellulose, undegraded hemicellulose sugars, reactive lignin and lignosulfonates, and is characterized by efficient recovery of chemicals.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The hydrolysis of cellulose (cellulolysis) produces simple sugars that can be fermented into alcohol.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] There are two major cellulolysis processes: chemical processes using acids, or enzymatic reactions using cellulases.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In the traditional methods developed in the 19th century and at the beginning of the 20th century, hydrolysis is performed by attacking the cellulose with an acid.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Dilute acid may be used under high heat and high pressure, or more concentrated acid can be used at lower temperatures and atmospheric pressure.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] A decrystallized cellulosic mixture of acid and sugars reacts in the presence of water to complete individual sugar molecules (hydrolysis).
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The product from this hydrolysis is then neutralized and yeast fermentation is used to produce ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] As mentioned, a significant obstacle to the dilute acid process is that the hydrolysis is so harsh that toxic degradation products are produced that can interfere with fermentation.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] BlueFire Renewables uses concentrated acid because it does not produce nearly as many fermentation inhibitors, but must be separated from the sugar stream for recycle [simulated moving bed chromatographic separation, for example] to be commercially attractive.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Agricultural Research Service scientists found they can access and ferment almost all of the remaining sugars in wheat straw.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The sugars are located in the plant's cell walls, which are notoriously difficult to break down.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] To access these sugars, scientists pretreated the wheat straw with alkaline peroxide, and then used specialized enzymes to break down the cell walls.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] This method produced 93 US gallons (350 L) of ethanol per ton of wheat straw.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Cellulose chains can be broken into glucose molecules by cellulase enzymes.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] This reaction occurs at body temperature in the stomachs of ruminants such as cattle and sheep, where the enzymes are produced by microbes.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] This process uses several enzymes at various stages of this conversion.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Using a similar enzymatic system, lignocellulosic materials can be enzymatically hydrolyzed at a relatively mild condition (50 °C and pH 5), thus enabling effective cellulose breakdown without the formation of byproducts that would otherwise inhibit enzyme activity.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] All major pretreatment methods, including dilute acid, require an enzymatic hydrolysis step to achieve high sugar yield for ethanol fermentation.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Fungal enzymes can be used to hydrolyze cellulose.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The raw material (often wood or straw) still has to be pre-treated to make it amenable to hydrolysis.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Traditionally, baker's yeast (*Saccharomyces cerevisiae*), has long been used in the brewery industry to produce ethanol from hexoses (six-carbon sugars).
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Due to the complex nature of the carbohydrates present in lignocellulosic biomass, a significant amount of xylose and arabinose (five-carbon sugars derived from the hemicellulose portion of the lignocellulose) is also present in the hydrolysate.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] For example, in the hydrolysate of corn stover, approximately 30% of the total fermentable sugars is xylose.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] As a result, the ability of the fermenting microorganisms to use the whole range of sugars available from the hydrolysate is vital to increase the economic competitiveness of cellulosic ethanol and potentially biobased proteins.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] At the turn of the millennium, metabolic engineering for microorganisms used in fuel ethanol production showed significant progress.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Besides *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*, microorganisms such as *Zymomonas mobilis* and *Escherichia coli* have been targeted through metabolic engineering for cellulosic ethanol production.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] An attraction towards alternative fermentation organism is its ability to ferment five carbon sugars improving the yield of the feed stock.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] This ability is often found in bacteria based organisms.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In the first decade of the 21st century, engineered yeasts have been described efficiently fermenting xylose, and arabinose, and even both together.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Yeast cells are especially attractive for cellulosic ethanol processes because they have been used in biotechnology for hundreds of years, are tolerant to high ethanol and inhibitor concentrations and can grow at low pH values to reduce bacterial contamination.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Some species of bacteria have been found capable of direct conversion of a cellulose substrate into ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] One example is *Clostridium thermocellum*, which uses a complex cellulosome to break down cellulose and synthesize ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] However, *C. thermocellum* also produces other products during cellulose metabolism, including acetate and lactate, in addition to ethanol, lowering the efficiency of the process.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Some research efforts are directed to optimizing ethanol production by genetically engineering bacteria that focus on the ethanol-producing pathway.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The gasification process does not rely on chemical decomposition of the cellulose chain (cellulolysis).
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Instead of breaking the cellulose into sugar molecules, the carbon in the raw material is converted into synthesis gas, using what amounts to partial combustion.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The carbon monoxide, carbon dioxide and hydrogen may then be fed into a special kind of fermenter.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Instead of sugar fermentation with yeast, this process uses *Clostridium ljungdahlii* bacteria.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] This microorganism will ingest carbon monoxide, carbon dioxide and hydrogen and produce ethanol and water.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] A 2002 study has found another *Clostridium* bacterium that seems to be twice as efficient in making ethanol from carbon monoxide as the one mentioned above.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Alternatively, the synthesis gas from gasification may be fed to a catalytic reactor where it is used to produce ethanol and other higher alcohols through a thermochemical process.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] This process can also generate other types of liquid fuels, an alternative concept successfully demonstrated by the Montreal-based company Enerkem at their facility in Westbury, Quebec.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Studies are intensively conducted to develop economic methods to convert both cellulose and hemicellulose to ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Fermentation of glucose, the main product of cellulose hydrolyzate, to ethanol is an already established and efficient technique.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] However, conversion of xylose, the pentose sugar of hemicellulose hydrolyzate, is a limiting factor, especially in the presence of glucose.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Moreover, it cannot be disregarded as hemicellulose will increase the efficiency and cost-effectiveness of cellulosic ethanol production.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Sakamoto (2012) et al. show the potential of genetic engineering microbes to express hemicellulase enzymes.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] 2. assimilate xylose by expression of xylose reductase and xylitol dehydrogenase.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The strain was able to convert rice straw hydrolyzate to ethanol, which contains hemicellulosic components.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Moreover, it was able to produce 2.5x more ethanol than the control strain, showing the highly effective process of cell surface-engineering to produce ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Ethanol burns more cleanly and more efficiently than gasoline.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Because plants consume carbon dioxide as they grow, bioethanol has an overall lower carbon footprint than fossil fuels.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Substituting ethanol for oil can also reduce a country's dependence on oil imports.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Commercial production of cellulosic ethanol, which unlike corn and sugarcane would not compete with food production, would be highly attractive since it would alleviate pressure on these foodcrops.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Although its processing costs are higher, the price of cellulose biomass is much cheaper than that of grains or fruits.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Moreover, since cellulose is the main component of plants, the whole plant can be harvested, rather than just the fruit or seeds.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] This results in much better yields; for instance, switchgrass yields twice as much ethanol per acre as corn.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Biomass materials for cellulose production require fewer inputs, such as fertilizer, herbicides, and their extensive roots improve soil quality, reduce erosion, and increase nutrient capture.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The overall carbon footprint and global warming potential of cellulosic ethanol are considerably lower (see chart) and the net energy output is several times higher than that of corn-based ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The potential raw material is also plentiful.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Around 44% of household waste generated worldwide consists of food and greens.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] An estimated 323 million tons of cellulose-containing raw materials which could be used to create ethanol are thrown away each year in US alone.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] This includes 36.8 million dry tons of urban wood wastes, 90.5 million dry tons of primary mill residues, 45 million dry tons of forest residues, and 150.7 million dry tons of corn stover and wheat straw.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Moreover, even land marginal for agriculture could be planted with cellulose-producing crops, such as switchgrass, resulting in enough production to substitute for all the current oil imports into the United States.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Paper, cardboard, and packaging comprise around 17% of global household waste; although some of this is recycled.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] As these products contain cellulose, they are transformable into cellulosic ethanol, which would avoid the production of methane, a potent greenhouse gas, during decomposition.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The main overall drawback of ethanol fuel is its lower fuel economy compared to gasoline when using ethanol in an engine designed for gasoline with a lower compression ratio.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The main disadvantage of cellulosic ethanol is its high cost and complexity of production, which has been the main impediment to its commercialization.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Although the global bioethanol market is sizable (around 110 billion liters in 2019), the vast majority is made from corn or sugarcane, not cellulose.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In 2007, the cost of producing ethanol from cellulosic sources was estimated ca.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] USD 2.65 per gallon (€0.58 per liter), which is around 2–3 times more expensive than ethanol made from corn.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] However, the cellulosic ethanol market remains relatively small and reliant on government subsidies.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The US government originally set cellulosic ethanol targets gradually ramping up from 1 billion liters in 2011 to 60 billion liters in 2022.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] However, these annual goals have almost always been waived after it became clear there was no chance of meeting them.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Most of the plants to produce cellulosic ethanol were canceled or abandoned in the early 2010s.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Plants built or financed by DuPont, General Motors and BP, among many others, were closed or sold.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] As of 2018, only one major plant remains in the US.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In order for it to be grown on a large-scale production, cellulose biomass must compete with existing uses of agricultural land, mainly for the production of crop commodities.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Of the United States' 2.26 billion acres (9.1 million km2) of unsubmerged land, 33% are forestland, 26% pastureland and grassland, and 20% crop land.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Departments of Energy and Agriculture in 2005 suggested that 1.3 billion dry tons of biomass is theoretically available for ethanol use while maintaining an acceptable impact on forestry, agriculture.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Currently, cellulose is more difficult and more expensive to process into ethanol than corn or sugarcane.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The US Department of Energy estimated in 2007 that it costs about $2.20 per gallon to produce cellulosic ethanol, which is 2–3 times much as ethanol from corn.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Enzymes that destroy plant cell wall tissue cost US$0.40 per gallon of ethanol compared to US$0.03 for corn.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] However, cellulosic biomass is cheaper to produce than corn, because it requires fewer inputs, such as energy, fertilizer, herbicide, and is accompanied by less soil erosion and improved soil fertility.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Additionally, nonfermentable and unconverted solids left after making ethanol can be burned to provide the fuel needed to operate the conversion plant and produce electricity.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Energy used to run corn-based ethanol plants is derived from coal and natural gas.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The Institute for Local Self-Reliance estimates the cost of cellulosic ethanol from the first generation of commercial plants will be in the $1.90–$2.25 per gallon range, excluding incentives.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] This compares to the current cost of $1.20–$1.50 per gallon for ethanol from corn and the current retail price of over $4.00 per gallon for regular gasoline (which is subsidized and taxed).
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Cellulases and hemicellulases used in the production of cellulosic ethanol are more expensive compared to their first generation counterparts.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Enzymes required for maize grain ethanol production cost US$ 2.64-5.28 per cubic meter of ethanol produced.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Enzymes for cellulosic ethanol production are projected to cost US$ 79.25/m3US$ EtOH, meaning they are 20-40 times more expensive.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The cost differences are attributed to quantity required.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The cellulase family of enzymes have a one to two order smaller magnitude of efficiency.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Therefore, it requires 40 to 100 times more of the enzyme to be present in its production, about 15-25 kilograms of enzyme per ton of biomass (2009 estimate).
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Enzymes as a result comprise 20-40% of the costs for cellulosic ethanol production.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] There are also relatively high capital costs associated with the long incubation times for the vessel that perform enzymatic hydrolysis.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] A more recent (2016) estimate reports that 10 kg of enzyme can be used per metric ton of dry biomass feedstock.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The enzyme cost fraction depends on how (and where) the cellulase enzyme is produced.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] For enzyme produced off-site, the fraction is 36%; for production on-site in a separate plant, the fraction is 29%; for integrated enzyme production, the fraction is 13%.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] One of the key benefits of integrated production is that biomass instead of glucose is the used as the growth medium for enzyme production.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] It also makes the resulting cellulosic ethanol a 100% second-generation biofuel, i.e., it uses no "food for fuel".
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In general there are two types of feedstocks: **forest (woody) Biomass** and **agricultural biomass**.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In the US, about 1.4 billion dry tons of biomass can be sustainably produced annually.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] About 370 million tons or 30% are forest biomass.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Forest biomass has higher cellulose and lignin content and lower hemicellulose and ash content than agricultural biomass.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Because of the difficulties and low ethanol yield in fermenting pretreatment hydrolysate, especially those with very high 5 carbon hemicellulose sugars such as xylose, forest biomass has significant advantages over agricultural biomass.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Forest biomass also has high density which significantly reduces transportation cost.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] It can be harvested year around which eliminates long-term storage.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The close to zero ash content of forest biomass significantly reduces dead load in transportation and processing.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] To meet the needs for biodiversity, forest biomass will be an important biomass feedstock supply mix in the future biobased economy.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] However, forest biomass is much more recalcitrant than agricultural biomass.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In 2009, the USDA Forest Products Laboratory together with the University of Wisconsin–Madison developed efficient technologies that can overcome the strong recalcitrance of forest (woody) biomass including those of softwood species that have low xylan content.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Short-rotation intensive culture or tree farming can offer an almost unlimited opportunity for forest biomass production.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Woodchips from slashes and tree tops and saw dust from saw mills, and waste paper pulp are forest biomass feedstocks for cellulosic ethanol production.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Food production produces waste in the form of inedible lignocellulosic biomass: stover, sugarcane bagasse, straw, etc.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Being lignocellulosic, a majority of their mass is cellulose, hemicellulose, and lignin.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Their nature as waste has led to sustained interest in converting them into useful materials including bioethanol.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] DuPont's Nevada pilot plant for converting corn stover to bioethanol ended in failure.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The German company Verbio purchased the plant with a goal to convert it to biomethane production.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Switchgrass is an approved cover crop for land protected under the federal Conservation Reserve Program (CRP).
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] CRP is a government program that pays producers a fee for not growing crops on land on which crops recently grew.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] This program reduces soil erosion, enhances water quality, and increases wildlife habitat.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] CRP land serves as a habitat for upland game, such as pheasants and ducks, and a number of insects.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Switchgrass for biofuel production has been considered for use on Conservation Reserve Program (CRP) land, which could increase ecological sustainability and lower the cost of the CRP program.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] However, CRP rules would have to be modified to allow this economic use of the CRP land.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] It was suggested in 1999 that Kudzu may become a valuable source of biomass.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Fueled by subsidies and grants, a boom in cellulosic ethanol research and pilot plants occurred in the early 2000s.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Companies such as Iogen, POET, and Abengoa built refineries that can process biomass and turn it into ethanol, while companies such as DuPont, Diversa, Novozymes, and Dyadic invested in enzyme research.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] However, most of these plants were canceled or closed in the early 2010s as technical obstacles proved too difficult to overcome.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] As of 2018, only one cellulosic ethanol plant remained operational.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In the later 2010s, various companies occasionally attempted smaller-scale efforts at commercializing cellulosic ethanol, although such ventures generally remain at experimental scales and often dependent on subsidies.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The companies Granbio, Raízen and the Centro de Tecnologia Canavieira each run a pilot-scale facility operate in Brazil, which together produce around 30 million liters in 2019.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Iogen, which started as an enzyme maker in 1991 and re-oriented itself to focus primarily on cellulosic ethanol in 2013, owns many patents for cellulosic ethanol production and provided the technology for the Raízen plant.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Other companies developing cellulosic ethanol technology as of 2021 are Inbicon (Denmark); companies operating or planning pilot production plants include New Energy Blue (US), Sekab (Sweden) and Clariant (in Romania).
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] Abengoa, a Spanish company with cellulosic ethanol assets, became insolvent in 2021.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The Australian Renewable Energy Agency, along with state and local governments, partially funded a pilot plant in 2017 and 2020 in New South Wales as part of efforts to diversify the regional economy away from coal mining.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] From 2006, the US Federal government began promoting the development of ethanol from cellulosic feedstocks.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In May 2008, Congress passed a new farm bill that contained funding for the commercialization of second-generation biofuels, including cellulosic ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The *Food, Conservation, and Energy Act of 2008* provided for grants covering up to 30% of the cost of developing and building demonstration-scale biorefineries for producing "advanced biofuels," which effectively included all fuels not produced from corn kernel starch.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] It also allowed for loan guarantees of up to $250 million for building commercial-scale biorefineries.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In January 2011, the USDA approved $405 million in loan guarantees through the 2008 Farm Bill to support the commercialization of cellulosic ethanol at three facilities owned by Coskata, Enerkem and INEOS New Planet BioEnergy.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The projects represent a combined 73 million US gallons (280,000 m3) per year production capacity and will begin producing cellulosic ethanol in 2012.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] The USDA also released a list of advanced biofuel producers who will receive payments to expand the production of advanced biofuels.
[src:bioconversion/cellulosic-ethanol] In July 2011, the US Department of Energy gave in $105 million in loan guarantees to POET for a commercial-scale plant to be built Emmetsburg, Iowa.
[src:bioconversion/clostridium-ljungdahlii] This species can ferment certain components of syngas into ethanol.
[src:bioconversion/clostridium-ljungdahlii] It also possesses properties of electrosynthesis, producing acetate on cathodes.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] There are conflicting definitions in the literature for selectivity and yield, so each author's intended definition should be verified.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] Conversion can be defined for (semi-)batch and continuous reactors and as instantaneous and overall conversion.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] where $\nu _{i}$ and $\mu _{j}$ are the stoichiometric coefficients.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] For multiple parallel reactions, the definitions can also be applied, either per reaction or using the limiting reaction.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] Conversion can be separated into instantaneous conversion and overall conversion.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] For continuous processes the two are the same, for batch and semi-batch there are important differences.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] Furthermore, for multiple reactants, conversion can be defined overall or per reactant.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] In this setting there are different definitions.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] with ${\dot {n}}_{i}$ as the change of moles with time of species i.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] It can be used to indicate whether reservoirs are built up and it is ideally close to 1.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] When the feed stops, its value is not defined.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] Yield in general refers to the amount of a specific product (*p* in 1..*m*) formed per mole of reactant consumed (Definition 1).
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] However, it is also defined as the amount of product produced per amount of product that could be produced (Definition 2).
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] If not all of the limiting reactant has reacted, the two definitions contradict each other.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] Instantaneous selectivity is the production rate of one component per production rate of another component.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] For overall selectivity the same problem of the conflicting definitions exists.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] Generally, it is defined as the number of moles of desired product per the number of moles of undesired product (Definition 1).
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] However, the definitions of the total amount of reactant to form a product per total amount of reactant consumed is used (Definition 2) as well as the total amount of desired product formed per total amount of limiting reactant consumed (Definition 3).
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] This last definition is the same as definition 1 for yield.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] For the following abstract example and the amounts depicted on the right, the following calculation can be performed with the above definitions, either in batch or a continuous reactor.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] There are 100 mol of A at the beginning or at the entry to the continuous reactor and 10 mol A, 72 mol B and 18 mol C at the end of the reaction or the exit of the continuous reactor.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] In this reaction, 90% of substance A is converted (consumed), but only 80% of the 90% is converted to the desired substance B and 20% to undesired by-products C.
[src:bioconversion/conversion-chemistry] So, conversion of A is 90%, selectivity for B 80% and yield of substance B 72%.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] The term "cortisone" is frequently misused to mean either any corticosteroid or hydrocortisone, which is in fact cortisol.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Many who speak of receiving a "cortisone shot" or taking "cortisone" are more likely receiving hydrocortisone or one of many other, much more potent synthetic corticosteroids.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Cortisone can be administered as a prodrug, meaning it has to be converted by the body (specifically the liver, converting it into cortisol) after administration to be effective.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] It is used to treat a variety of ailments and can be administered intravenously, orally, intra-articularly (into a joint), or transcutaneously.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Cortisone suppresses various elements of the immune system, thus reducing inflammation and attendant pain and swelling.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Risks exist, in particular in the long-term use of cortisone.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] However, using cortisone only results in very mild activity, and very often more potent steroids are used instead.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] It must be converted to cortisol by the action of 11β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase type 1.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] This primarily happens in the liver, the main site at which cortisone becomes cortisol after oral or systemic injection, and can thus have a pharmacological effect.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] After application to the skin or injection into a joint, local cells that express 11β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase type 1 instead convert it to active cortisol.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] A cortisone injection may provide short-term pain relief and may reduce the swelling from inflammation of a joint, tendon, or bursa in, for example, the joints of the knee, elbow and shoulder and into a broken coccyx.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Cortisone is used by dermatologists to treat keloids, relieve the symptoms of eczema and atopic dermatitis, and stop the development of sarcoidosis.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Oral use of cortisone has a number of potential systemic adverse effects, including asthma, hyperglycemia, insulin resistance, diabetes mellitus, osteoporosis, anxiety, depression, amenorrhoea, cataracts, glaucoma, Cushing's syndrome, increased risk of infections, and impaired growth.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] With topical application, it can lead to thinning of the skin, impaired wound healing, increased skin pigmentation, tendon rupture, and skin infections (including abscesses).
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Cortisone is a corticosteroid, functioning as both a glucocorticoid and mineralocorticoid.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Cortisone itself is inactive and instead acts as a prodrug or prohormone of cortisol (hydrocortisone), which is responsible for its biological activity.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] It is metabolized into cortisol via the actions of 11β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase 1 (11β-HSD1).
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Cortisol can also be metabolized back into cortisone by the actions of 11β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase 2 (11β-HSD2).
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Through conversion into cortisol, cortisone acts indirectly as an agonist of the corticosteroid receptors, including the glucocorticoid receptor (GR) and mineralocorticoid receptor (MR).
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] In addition, through cortisol, it acts indirectly as an agonist of membrane corticosteroid receptors, including membrane glucocorticoid receptors (mGRs) and membrane mineralocorticoid receptors (mMRs).
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Cortisone has about 80% of the oral potency of hydrocortisone as both a glucocorticoid and mineralocorticoid when used clinically in humans.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Relatedly, a dose of 25 mg cortisone is equivalent to about 20 mg hydrocortisone.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] In addition to its corticosteroid activity, cortisone has been reported to be a highly potent negative allosteric modulator of the GABAA receptor (1 pM–10 nM).
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] This was demonstrated specifically in guinea pig ileum tissue.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Cortisone was first identified by the American chemists Edward Calvin Kendall and Harold L.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Mason while researching at the Mayo Clinic.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] During the discovery process, cortisone was known as compound E (while cortisol was known as compound F).
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Hench and colleagues discovered that large doses of injected cortisone were effective in the treatment of patients with severe rheumatoid arthritis.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Kendall was awarded the 1950 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine along with Philip Showalter Hench and Tadeusz Reichstein for the discovery of the structure and function of adrenal cortex hormones including cortisone.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Pfiffner had separately isolated the compound prior to the discovery made by Mason and Kendall, but failed to recognize its biological significance.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Mason's contributions to the crystallization and characterization of the compound have generally been forgotten outside of the Mayo Clinic.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Cortisone was first produced commercially by Merck & Co. in 1948 or 1949.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] On September 30, 1949, Percy Julian announced an improvement in the process of producing cortisone from bile acids.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] This eliminated the need to use osmium tetroxide, a rare, expensive, and dangerous chemical.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] In the UK in the early 1950s, John Cornforth and Kenneth Callow at the National Institute for Medical Research collaborated with Glaxo to produce cortisone from hecogenin from sisal plants.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Cortisone is one of several end-products of a process called steroidogenesis.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] This process starts with the synthesis of cholesterol, which then proceeds through a series of modifications in the adrenal gland to become any one of many steroid hormones.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] One end-product of this pathway is cortisol.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] For cortisol to be released from the adrenal gland, a cascade of signaling occurs.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Corticotropin-releasing hormone released from the hypothalamus stimulates corticotrophs in the anterior pituitary to release ACTH, which relays the signal to the adrenal cortex.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Here, the zona fasciculata and zona reticularis, in response to ACTH, secrete glucocorticoids, in particular cortisol.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] In various peripheral tissues, notably the kidneys, cortisol is inactivated to cortisone by the enzyme corticosteroid 11-beta-dehydrogenase isozyme 2.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] This is crucial because cortisol is a potent mineralocorticoid and would cause havoc with electrolyte levels (raising blood sodium and lowering blood potassium levels) and raise blood pressure if it were not inactivated in the kidneys.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Because cortisone must be converted to cortisol before being active as a glucocorticoid, its activity is less than simply administering cortisol directly (80–90%).
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Abuse and addiction to cortisone was the subject of the 1956 motion picture *Bigger Than Life*, produced by and starring James Mason.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Though it was a box-office flop upon its initial release, many modern critics hail the film as a masterpiece and brilliant indictment of contemporary attitudes toward mental illness and addiction.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] In 1963, Jean-Luc Godard named it one of the ten greatest American sound films ever made.
[src:bioconversion/cortisone] Kennedy was regularly administered corticosteroids such as cortisone as a treatment for Addison's disease.
